AnnotationURLCitation(end_index=38301, start_index=38075, title='Antitrust & Competition Healthcare Quarterly Update Q2 2024 | Insights & Resources | Goodwin', type='url_citation', url='https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/09/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-quarterly-update-q2-2024#:~:text=,the%20Federal%20Trade%20Commission%E2%80%99s%20complaint'), AnnotationURLCitation(end_index=38496, start_index=38302, title='A Year-End Report for Healthcare Antitrust and What to Expect Later in 2025 | Insights | Holland & Knight', type='url_citation', url='https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=that%20healthcare%20transactions%20will%20remain,1')], text='# Federal Enforcement: Heightened Scrutiny of Healthcare Mergers\n\n**Aggressive Review of Deals:** U.S. antitrust agencies – the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) and Department of Justice (DOJ) – have sharply increased their scrutiny of mergers and acquisitions in the healthcare sector. In 2023, regulators challenged an unusually high number of healthcare deals, reflecting a belief that past merger review was too permissive ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=jointly%20announced%20the%20release%20of,Guidelines%20would%20remain%20in%20effect)) ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)). The FTC successfully **blocked several horizontal mergers** (e.g. hospital systems combining in the same region) using traditional antitrust theories that such deals would eliminate head-to-head competitors and harm patients through higher prices or lower quality ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=Commission%20,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)). Notably, in late 2023 a federal judge sided with the FTC to halt **IQVIA’s acquisition of Propel Media**, finding the merger of two leading healthcare marketing firms would stifle competition ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=FTC%20success%20in%20challenge%20to,a%20prolonged%20Second%20Request%20investigation)). Regulators are also pushing the boundaries with *novel theories of harm*: the new Merger Guidelines issued in late 2023 signal that enforcers will consider **impacts on labor (workers)** and **misuse of data** when evaluating healthcare mergers, and they explicitly caution that even minority shareholdings or serial acquisitions can raise antitrust concerns ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=agencies%20will%20continue%20to%20closely,from%20this%20path%20in%202024)) ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=jointly%20announced%20the%20release%20of,Guidelines%20would%20remain%20in%20effect)). This represents a more aggressive policy stance that **expands the types of transactions subject to challenge**, on the view that rampant consolidation in healthcare is driving up costs for consumers ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=jointly%20announced%20the%20release%20of,Guidelines%20would%20remain%20in%20effect)).\n\n**Challenging Big Pharma and Vertical Deals:** For the first time in over a decade, the FTC moved to block a major **pharmaceutical merger** on competitive grounds. In 2023 the FTC sued to stop Amgen’s $27.8 billion acquisition of Horizon Therapeutics – **even though the companies had no overlapping products** – arguing the deal would let Amgen use its portfolio power to undermine potential rivals to Horizon’s drugs and “maintain a monopoly” ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2023/05/16/ftc-amgen-horizon#:~:text=The%20Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,the%20FTC%20has%20permitted%20pharmaceutical)). (Historically the FTC allowed pharma mergers if overlapping drugs were divested, so this case marked a **tougher approach** ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2023/05/16/ftc-amgen-horizon#:~:text=purchasing%20Horizon%20Therapeutics%2C%20a%20rare,10%20billion%20between%202010%20and)).) The FTC ultimately settled that case by having Amgen agree not to bundle Horizon’s medications with its own, but the bold initial challenge signaled to the industry that **mergers lacking direct overlaps can still face antitrust attack**. Similarly, officials are casting a wary eye on vertical integration in health care – for example, the DOJ (joined by several states) **sued in late 2024 to block UnitedHealth Group’s proposed $3.3 billion takeover of Amedisys**, a home-health provider, over concerns a healthcare giant’s expanding empire could hurt competition in local markets ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/us-sues-block-unitedhealths-33-bln-purchase-amedisys-2024-11-12/#:~:text=2024,in%20the%20home%20health%20services)). (UnitedHealth’s Optum unit has been acquiring physician groups, clinics, and home care companies, raising alarms about a single company controlling many facets of care.) These enforcement moves – alongside the Biden Administration’s 2021 executive order calling out hospital consolidation and healthcare pricing issues – underscore that **antitrust officials are closely scrutinizing both horizontal and vertical deals** in healthcare and aren’t shying away from court fights.\n\n**New Guidelines and Filing Rules:** The antitrust agencies updated their Merger Guidelines and filing requirements to support this tougher enforcement climate. The **2023 Draft Merger Guidelines (finalized in late 2023)** explicitly highlight the healthcare sector, cautioning that the loss of competition can lead to higher medical costs and worse care outcomes. The Guidelines also emphasize that mergers increasing market concentration beyond certain thresholds are presumptively unlawful – reviving strict standards from earlier case law – and they endorse scrutiny of deals that **entrench power across multiple markets or along supply chains** ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=jointly%20announced%20the%20release%20of,Guidelines%20would%20remain%20in%20effect)). In practical terms, the FTC has enacted new **Hart–Scott–Rodino (HSR) filing rules** that demand far more information about deals at the time of notification ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=On%20Oct,The%20Final)). As of 2024, merging parties must disclose details like overlaps in product and service lines, distribution agreements, and the deal’s strategic rationale ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=On%20Oct,The%20Final)). This change (effective **late 2024**) significantly increases the burden of filing – the FTC estimates the average filing will take *around 100 hours of work*, up from ~37 hours previously ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=On%20Oct,The%20Final)). The goal is to catch subtler anticompetitive issues early, particularly in complex industries like healthcare where a merger’s impact on patients or innovation may not be obvious from basic revenue data.\n\n**DOJ Health Care Task Force:** In addition to rule changes, the DOJ Antitrust Division in 2024 formed a dedicated **“Task Force on Health Care Monopolies and Collusion”** to coordinate enforcement in this industry ([www.healthcareinsights.md](https://www.healthcareinsights.md/blog/2024/5/10/todays-news-and-commentary#:~:text=Assistant%20Attorney%20General%20Jonathan%20Kanter,businesses%20and%20entrepreneurs%2C%20including%20issues)) ([www.healthcareinsights.md](https://www.healthcareinsights.md/blog/2024/5/10/todays-news-and-commentary#:~:text=regarding%20payer,%E2%80%9D)). This inter-disciplinary task force – involving prosecutors, economists, physicians, and data scientists – is examining a wide range of concerns: **hospital-insurer consolidation, serial acquisitions of physician practices, healthcare labor markets, quality of care, billing practices, health IT, and even access to sensitive health data** ([www.healthcareinsights.md](https://www.healthcareinsights.md/blog/2024/5/10/todays-news-and-commentary#:~:text=The%20HCMC%20will%20consider%20widespread,%E2%80%9D)). By marshalling expertise across civil and criminal enforcement, the DOJ aims to identify anti-competitive conduct **beyond just mergers**, such as wage-fixing or collusive contracting in healthcare markets. (In fact, the DOJ saw its *first-ever criminal conviction* for labor-market antitrust in April 2025, when a home-health agency executive was convicted of conspiring to fix nurse wages ([www.antitrustalert.com](https://www.antitrustalert.com/category/healthcare-antitrust/#:~:text=DOJ%20Secures%20Its%20First,Criminal%20Antitrust%20Labor%20Market%20Trial)) – a sign that **antitrust law in healthcare is expanding into areas like employment practices**.) Overall, at the federal level the latest developments point to a more interventionist approach: regulators are requiring more upfront information, applying new theories, and dedicating special resources to **police consolidation in healthcare**.\n\n# Spotlight on Private Equity “Roll-Ups” in Healthcare\n\nA **major development in healthcare antitrust** is the targeting of private equity-led consolidation strategies. Private equity (PE) firms have been rapidly buying up medical practices, clinics, and specialist groups – often via a series of smaller acquisitions that individually fly under the radar. Studies indicate that **roughly 90% of PE-driven healthcare transactions are small enough to fall below federal HSR reporting thresholds** (which rose to $119.5 million in 2024) ([www.americanbar.org](https://www.americanbar.org/groups/business_law/resources/business-law-today/2024-may/may-2024-brief-mergers-acquisitions/#:~:text=Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,particularly%20in%20smaller%20healthcare%20markets)). This means many roll-ups (serial acquisitions) haven’t received federal antitrust review, even though collectively they can reduce competition in local markets ([www.americanbar.org](https://www.americanbar.org/groups/business_law/resources/business-law-today/2024-may/may-2024-brief-mergers-acquisitions/#:~:text=%24111,particularly%20in%20smaller%20healthcare%20markets)). In response, **antitrust enforcers have put PE in the crosshairs**. The FTC’s first lawsuit against a healthcare roll-up came in September 2023, when it sued PE firm Welsh, Carson, Anderson & Stowe over its strategy of consolidating anesthesiology practices in Texas ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=In%20September%202023%2C%20the%20FTC,may%20be%20the%20first%20of)). The FTC alleged that Welsh Carson orchestrated a scheme (through its portfolio company USAP) to buy up anesthesia provider groups and **corner the market** on hospital anesthesia services, driving up prices for patients and insurers ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=In%20September%202023%2C%20the%20FTC,may%20be%20the%20first%20of)). This bold “roll-up” case was widely seen as a *test* of whether antitrust law could reach a PE firm’s pattern of acquisitions.\n\n**Mixed Results in the Courts:** The enforcement push against PE roll-ups has encountered some legal hurdles. In May 2024, a federal judge *dismissed* the FTC’s claims against Welsh Carson, ruling that the agency’s lawsuit had not adequately tied the investor itself to antitrust violations by its portfolio company ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=focus%20was%20not%20always%20successful,minority%20investors%20in%20subsidiary%20companies)). The court’s dismissal clarified that **Section 13(b) of the FTC Act** (which allows the FTC to seek injunctions) cannot be used expansively to drag in outside minority investors unless there’s clear evidence of ongoing or imminent law violations ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=District%20Court%20for%20the%20Southern,minority%20investors%20in%20subsidiary%20companies)). In other words, the judge was wary of treating a PE owner as directly liable for a consolidation strategy executed via a subsidiary. This was a significant setback for the FTC’s novel approach to **punish PE firms for monopolistic roll-ups**. However, the story didn’t end there – in January 2025 the FTC reached a **settlement** with Welsh Carson to resolve potential administrative charges ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=that%20of%20stopping%20seemingly%20unfair,any%20future%20investments%20in%20anesthesia)). Under that settlement, the firm agreed to **curb its influence and notify regulators of future deals**: for example, Welsh Carson must limit its board seats and ownership stake in USAP, **obtain FTC approval before any new investments in anesthesia practices nationwide**, and give 30-days advance notice if it tries to acquire other hospital-based physician groups ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=announced%20a%20settlement%20with%20Welsh,based%20physician%20practices%20nationwide)). These unprecedented conditions function like ongoing antitrust guardrails, effectively placing a PE firm under monitoring for future healthcare acquisitions. The outcome signals that, despite a court rebuff, regulators are still finding ways to rein in serial acquisitions – and PE firms may face more scrutiny and **behavioral restrictions** when they seek to build healthcare empires.\n\n**Broader Impact and Political Pressure:** The intense focus on private equity’s role in healthcare extends beyond the FTC’s actions. Policymakers and researchers have raised alarms that PE ownership can lead to **cost-cutting at the expense of quality** – for instance, staffing reductions or surprise billing practices. In late 2024, the U.S. Senate Budget Committee released a report titled *“Profits Over Patients: The Harmful Effects of Private Equity on U.S. Health Care”*, concluding that PE investment often prioritizes short-term profits and can result in higher prices or diminished care quality in hospitals ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=Another%20example%20of%20the%20focus,provides%20in%20the%20healthcare%20industry)). This added political pressure bolsters the antitrust agencies’ resolve to scrutinize deals involving PE. We’re also seeing proposed legislation (at state and federal levels) specifically targeting PE acquisitions in health services. For example, some states have considered outright **bans on PE firms owning physician practices** or imposing special approval requirements (as discussed below). All of these developments indicate that **“roll-up” strategies are no longer flying under the radar** – they are front and center in antitrust discussions. Going forward, private equity buyers in healthcare should anticipate longer reviews, possible divestiture demands, and conditions to ensure competition isn’t harmed by a cumulative series of small deals.\n\n# Court Battles and Evolving Legal Standards\n\nThe recent wave of healthcare merger challenges has produced **mixed results in the courts**, leading to important legal developments. While antitrust enforcers have blocked some deals, judges have not sided with them in every case – refining the boundaries of antitrust law in this industry:\n\n- **Hospital Merger Injunctions – Wins and Losses:** Hospital consolidations remain a prime target for the FTC, but a notable 2024 ruling showed the FTC doesn’t win them all. In June 2024, a federal judge in North Carolina **denied the FTC’s request to preliminarily block Novant Health’s $320 million acquisition of two hospitals** from a rival system ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/ftc-loses-bid-block-320-million-hospital-merger-north-carolina-2024-06-05/#:~:text=A%20U,June%2026%2C%20with%20both%20sides)). The court found the FTC hadn’t met its burden to prove the deal would likely lessen competition substantially – even though Novant would control an estimated 65% of the local inpatient market. The judge noted potential **offsetting benefits** of the merger for those struggling community hospitals and questioned some of the FTC’s market definitions ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/ftc-loses-bid-block-320-million-hospital-merger-north-carolina-2024-06-05/#:~:text=Commission%27s%20,case%20is%20a%20part%20of)). This was a setback for the FTC’s hospital enforcement program, which had successfully stopped other mergers (e.g. in New Jersey and Utah in recent years) using more traditional analysis when hospitals were clear-cut competitors. The Novant case underscores that courts will still demand robust, fact-specific evidence of harm – especially if defendants argue that a merger may *improve* healthcare access or quality. It’s a reminder that **antitrust law requires weighing pro-competitive benefits against anti-competitive risks**, and healthcare defendants are using quality/improvement arguments to rebut the government’s claims.\n\n- **State Action (COPA Laws) vs. FTC:** Another legal development has been the tension between federal antitrust enforcement and **state laws that shield healthcare mergers**. Some states implement “**Certificate of Public Advantage (COPA)**” laws, which allow hospital systems to merge under state oversight (often to preserve struggling hospitals) and **immunize them from federal antitrust claims**. The FTC has long criticized COPA arrangements as enabling monopolies, but it suffered a defeat in 2023 trying to challenge them ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=in%20the%20FTC%E2%80%99s%20campaign%20against,antitrust%20laws%20supersede%20state%20COPA)). In a Louisiana case, a federal court **rejected the FTC’s argument that federal antitrust law should trump the state’s COPA statute**, firmly upholding the legality of the state-approved hospital merger ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=through%20Louisiana%E2%80%99s%20COPA%20statute%2C%20and,12)). The judge ruled that because the transaction was explicitly **authorized by state law and supervised by state authorities**, it was exempt from federal antitrust review under the “state-action” doctrine ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=campaigned%20against%20state,benefits%20of%20the%20deal%20outweigh)). This outcome affirms that, absent congressional change, COPA-sanctioned deals are largely beyond the FTC’s reach. Consequently, **some hospital systems in rural areas or smaller states have a path to consolidate by seeking a COPA from the state**, effectively trading competitive free-market oversight for state regulatory oversight. The FTC has expressed concern that this undermines antitrust enforcement, but courts indicate that **as long as states follow the requirements of active supervision, these mergers can proceed**. This development may encourage more hospitals to lobby for state COPA laws, although only a minority of states currently have them.\n\n- **Novel Theories Tested:** Courts are also grappling with how far new antitrust theories can go in healthcare M&A cases. The FTC’s **“bundled products” theory in pharma** (as seen in the Amgen/Horizon case) and the concept of mergers harming **labor markets (monopsony)** are relatively untested in litigation. While the Amgen case didn’t go to a final court decision (due to a settlement), it raised the question of whether a merger can be blocked for enabling anti-competitive *behavior* (like bundling different drugs in negotiations) even if it doesn’t eliminate a direct competitor. Similarly, the DOJ’s statements suggest that a hospital merger could be challenged for giving the combined system power to **push down nurses’ or doctors’ wages** (a monopsony harm) – a theory yet to be fully proven in court. Initial signs are that courts are cautious: they rely on established precedent that typically looks at **consumer prices and direct competition**, so enforcers will need strong evidence to succeed on these unconventional grounds. However, the inclusion of such theories in the new Merger Guidelines and public speeches means we may soon see test cases where the government argues a healthcare merger hurts not just patients as consumers, but also the **workers** who provide care or the **innovation pipeline** for new treatments. How courts rule on these arguments in upcoming cases will be a key development to watch, as it will determine the *scope* of antitrust law in the healthcare context moving forward.\n\n# State-Level Antitrust Measures on Healthcare Deals\n\nWith federal authorities stretched and many deals slipping under the radar, **state governments have started taking a more direct role in policing healthcare M&A**. The past two years have seen a flurry of state legislation and regulations aimed at increasing oversight of healthcare transactions:\n\n- **“Baby HSR” Laws – New Notification Requirements:** Numerous states are enacting their own **pre-merger notification mandates** for health sector deals. Unlike the federal HSR Act (which only requires notice for fairly large deals), these state laws kick in at much lower dollar thresholds or cover specific types of healthcare arrangements. **New York**, for example, implemented a **“Material Transactions” law in 2023** requiring that healthcare entities (hospitals, physician groups, insurance plans, clinical labs, pharmacies, etc.) give the state **90 days’ notice of any merger, acquisition, affiliation, joint venture, or similar transaction** meeting certain size criteria ([www.antitrustlawblog.com](https://www.antitrustlawblog.com/articles/healthcare-antitrust/#:~:text=The%20number%20of%20U,and%20Broader%29%20Areas%20of)) ([www.antitrustlawblog.com](https://www.antitrustlawblog.com/2025/04/articles/healthcare-antitrust/new-york-state-releases-much-anticipated-guidance-on-reporting-requirements-for-material-healthcare-transactions-as-budget-negotiations-near-conclusion-potentially-expanding-law-to-include-pre-closin/#:~:text=organization%2C%20or%20plan%20that%20provides,under%20the%20Material%20Transactions%20law)). The threshold is relatively low – **$25 million in combined annual revenue** for the parties – meaning even modest acquisitions or partnerships must be reported ([www.antitrustlawblog.com](https://www.antitrustlawblog.com/2025/04/articles/healthcare-antitrust/new-york-state-releases-much-anticipated-guidance-on-reporting-requirements-for-material-healthcare-transactions-as-budget-negotiations-near-conclusion-potentially-expanding-law-to-include-pre-closin/#:~:text=Clarification%20on%20the%20%2425%20Million,Threshold%20and%20%E2%80%9CDe%20Minimis%E2%80%9D%20Transactions)) ([www.antitrustlawblog.com](https://www.antitrustlawblog.com/2025/04/articles/healthcare-antitrust/new-york-state-releases-much-anticipated-guidance-on-reporting-requirements-for-material-healthcare-transactions-as-budget-negotiations-near-conclusion-potentially-expanding-law-to-include-pre-closin/#:~:text=The%20DOH%E2%80%99s%20examples%20clarify%20that,by%20%2425%20million%20or%20more)). The New York Department of Health can review these deals and even hold public hearings, adding transparency and allowing state officials to flag any competition concerns. **California** likewise passed a law (AB 2080) that took effect on January 1, 2024, requiring healthcare mergers and clinic acquisitions to be reported to the new Office of Health Care Affordability (OHCA) ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=California,have%20been%20reported%20to%20OHCA)). California’s regulations were updated mid-2024 to **cast an even wider net** – by mid-year, at least 11 transactions had already been reported to OHCA for review ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=California,have%20been%20reported%20to%20OHCA)). While California’s process is largely aimed at data collection and cost containment (the OHCA evaluates whether a deal might increase healthcare costs or undermine access), it creates a potential **pause** on deals until the state’s analysis is done. This trend of “Baby HSR” laws means that even if a deal is too small to alert the FTC, it may still face scrutiny and possible delay at the state level.\n\n- **Targeting Private Equity and Practice Acquisitions:** Many states are tailoring laws to address the very **private equity roll-ups** and rapid provider consolidation discussed above. **Massachusetts** is a prime example: since 2012 it has had a Healthcare Policy Commission (HPC) that monitors provider mergers for cost impacts, but in early 2025 the state expanded its law to shine a light on private equity investors ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=H,are%20in%20the%20following%20details)) ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=H.5159%20broadens%20the%20existing%2060,Massachusetts%20Health%20Policy%20Commission)). Under a new statute (H.5159, signed in Jan. 2025), Massachusetts broadened its mandatory health transaction reporting to include **any deal where a “significant private equity or investment entity” acquires a material stake in a healthcare provider or entity** ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=H.5159%20broadens%20the%20existing%2060,Massachusetts%20Health%20Policy%20Commission)) ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=,applicability%20of%20the%20amended%20law)). It also requires notice of **certain hospital real-estate transactions** (like sale-leaseback arrangements) and conversions of non-profit hospitals to for-profit status ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=1,the%20moment%2C%20many%20questions%20remain)). This law was crafted to increase transparency around **who is financing and controlling healthcare providers**, on the theory that ownership by PE or similar investors might warrant closer review. Other states are exploring even stricter measures: for instance, **Connecticut and Rhode Island** have debated limits on hospital ownership changes and **Minnesota** considered regulating physician practice management companies. Though not all proposals pass (California’s 2024 attempt to mandate *pre-approval* for any PE or hedge fund buying a healthcare entity was vetoed ([www.antitrustlawblog.com](https://www.antitrustlawblog.com/articles/healthcare-antitrust/#:~:text=On%20September%2028%2C%202024%2C%20Governor,of%20control%20of%20certain%20health))), the legislative trend is clearly toward **more oversight of acquisitions involving private investors** or those that could lead to provider monopolies in local markets.\n\n- **Broad Healthcare Merger Moratoria and Cost Oversight:** A few states have even gone as far as temporarily **banning certain mergers** or imposing cost controls on large systems. **Oregon** and **Washington** set up regulatory schemes requiring approval for mergers of hospitals or clinics above a low size threshold, focusing on whether the deal would reduce access or raise prices. Washington State made headlines in April 2025 by becoming the **first state to adopt the Uniform Antitrust Premerger Notification Act**, a law that actually applies to *all industries* but was driven in part by healthcare concerns ([www.antitrustalert.com](https://www.antitrustalert.com/category/healthcare-antitrust/#:~:text=Washington%20is%20the%20first%20state,includes%20significant%20penalties%20for%20noncompliance)). Washington’s law basically says if a merger requires a federal HSR filing and affects Washington, the same filing must be submitted to the state’s Attorney General ([www.antitrustalert.com](https://www.antitrustalert.com/category/healthcare-antitrust/#:~:text=Washington%20is%20the%20first%20state,includes%20significant%20penalties%20for%20noncompliance)). This ensures the state can independently review big healthcare deals (or any large deal) and even sue to block them alongside the federal agencies. On the other coast, **New York** not only has the notice law, but its Attorney General has been active in reviewing hospital mergers for antitrust issues, sometimes negotiating conditions or forcing abandonment of deals that the FTC might not have caught. States are also using **health commissions to monitor post-merger effects** – for example, Delaware’s Health Commission can require merging hospitals to report on pricing and quality for years afterwards. In sum, states are **filling gaps in enforcement** by catching smaller transactions and focusing on healthcare-specific metrics like patient costs, rural care availability, and whether investment-driven consolidations erode the quality of care.\n\nAll these developments at the state level mean that healthcare M&A now faces a **dual layer of antitrust oversight**: companies must navigate not only the FTC/DOJ process but also a patchwork of state reporting and approval rules. This can complicate deal timelines and strategies. However, it reflects policymakers’ concern that unchecked consolidation – whether it’s one giant hospital buying its competitor, or a private equity firm quietly amassing dozens of medical practices – can hurt consumers **even if** it escapes federal review. Going forward, we can expect continued experimentation by states, such as stricter merger **moratoria in healthcare “hot spots”** (e.g. limits on hospital mergers in highly consolidated regions) or new standards tying approval to commitments on price containment. Healthcare companies and investors must stay attuned to these state-law developments, as they are now a critical part of the **antitrust landscape for mergers and acquisitions**.\n\n# Key Takeaways and Outlook\n\n- **Antitrust Enforcement is Intensifying:** Recent years have seen a clear upswing in antitrust actions against healthcare mergers. Both the FTC and DOJ are more willing to challenge deals – even very large or novel ones – reflecting a view that consolidation has gone too far in the healthcare industry ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)) ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=jointly%20announced%20the%20release%20of,Guidelines%20would%20remain%20in%20effect)). From hospital systems and physician groups to health insurers and drug companies, no segment is off-limits. Merging parties should be prepared for closer scrutiny, longer investigations, and higher odds of litigation than in the past.\n\n- **New Theories and Broader Goals:** Antitrust enforcers are expanding their toolkit beyond classic price-and-market-share analysis. The **latest merger guidelines** emphasize potential harm to **workers (labor monopsony)** and to **innovation and data competition**, which are highly relevant in healthcare (e.g. the impact on nurse wages, or control of health data) ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=jointly%20announced%20the%20release%20of,Guidelines%20would%20remain%20in%20effect)). Regulators are also considering how a merger might facilitate future anti-competitive conduct (such as bundling products or exclusive contracting) even if it doesn’t create a monopoly overnight ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2023/05/16/ftc-amgen-horizon#:~:text=The%20Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,the%20FTC%20has%20permitted%20pharmaceutical)). This broader approach aligns with the Biden administration’s pro-competition agenda. Although there is some uncertainty about how aggressively these policies will continue under evolving leadership (the guidelines introduced in 2023 remain in effect into 2025 ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=approaches%20to%20merger%20review%20have,Guidelines%20would%20remain%20in%20effect))), **the overall trajectory is toward more vigilant antitrust enforcement in health care.**\n\n- **Courts as Crucial Arbiters:** The outcomes of recent cases show that **courts will ultimately refine the limits of antitrust law** in this arena. The FTC and DOJ have won significant victories blocking anti-competitive mergers, but they’ve also been **checked by judges when evidence of harm was deemed insufficient or when state policies conflicted with federal aims** ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/ftc-loses-bid-block-320-million-hospital-merger-north-carolina-2024-06-05/#:~:text=Commission%27s%20,case%20is%20a%20part%20of)) ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=through%20Louisiana%E2%80%99s%20COPA%20statute%2C%20and,12)). Going forward, watch for precedent-setting decisions – for example, if a court accepts or rejects a **labor harm theory** in a hospital merger, or how it handles a **Big Tech–meets–healthcare deal** (like a large data company buying a healthcare provider network). These decisions will shape how far agencies can go. So far, traditional horizontal mergers that create dominant local players are most likely to be blocked, whereas more novel theories must overcome skepticism. Companies should note that **even if they defeat a preliminary injunction (as Novant did) or evade federal jurisdiction (via a COPA law), enforcement pressure may continue through other means** – such as post-merger monitoring, state AG actions, or private lawsuits.\n\n- **State Enforcement is Here to Stay:** One of the latest and most significant developments is the rise of **state-level antitrust enforcement in healthcare**. States from New York to California to Massachusetts are not only **passing laws to review healthcare deals** ([www.antitrustlawblog.com](https://www.antitrustlawblog.com/articles/healthcare-antitrust/#:~:text=The%20number%20of%20U,and%20Broader%29%20Areas%20of)), but in some cases directly intervening to block or unwind mergers they find problematic. This decentralization means healthcare companies must engage with multiple regulators. A deal that sails through Washington could still snag in Sacramento or Albany. On the flip side, state initiatives could also complement federal efforts – for instance, by collecting data on smaller deals and market effects that the FTC can later use. We anticipate more states will adopt “mini-HSR” notification laws or strengthen their attorney generals’ authority to oversee health mergers in 2025 and beyond. The **patchwork of state rules** may be challenging for industry, but it’s a direct response to gaps perceived in federal enforcement (like the many sub-$119 million acquisitions that cumulatively reshape local markets ([www.americanbar.org](https://www.americanbar.org/groups/business_law/resources/business-law-today/2024-may/may-2024-brief-mergers-acquisitions/#:~:text=Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,particularly%20in%20smaller%20healthcare%20markets))).\n\n- **Continued Focus on Healthcare Costs and Competition:** Underlying these legal moves is a broad policy consensus that **healthcare consolidation has contributed to rising costs and needs to be checked**. Regulators cite studies linking hospital mergers to higher patient prices, or Nursing home chain buyouts to worse care outcomes. Thus, antitrust law is being wielded as one tool to address healthcare affordability and quality. We see this in the names of new state offices (e.g. “Health Care Affordability” in California) and in congressional rhetoric. Even if administrations change or specific cases falter, the **momentum for competitive healthcare markets** is likely to persist. Participants in the healthcare industry – hospitals, insurers, pharmaceutical companies, private equity funds, and others – should plan for a landscape where **mergers face more rigorous antitrust investigation than ever before**. In sum, the latest developments point to a tougher road for M&A in healthcare, as authorities at multiple levels push to prevent deals that could harm patients, payers, or the integrity of our healthcare system.  ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/09/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-quarterly-update-q2-2024#:~:text=,the%20Federal%20Trade%20Commission%E2%80%99s%20complaint)) ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=that%20healthcare%20transactions%20will%20remain,1))\n\n', type='output_text', logprobs=[])], role='assistant', status='completed', type='message'), output_index=77, sequence_number=8900, type='response.output_item.done')

AnnotationURLCitation(end_index=35888, start_index=35735, title='Healthcare / Antitrust | Antitrust Law Blog', type='url_citation', url='https://www.antitrustlawblog.com/articles/healthcare-antitrust/#:~:text=The%20number%20of%20U,and%20Broader%29%20Areas%20of'), AnnotationURLCitation(end_index=36936, start_index=36698, title='May 2024 in Brief: Mergers & Acquisitions', type='url_citation', url='https://www.americanbar.org/groups/business_law/resources/business-law-today/2024-may/may-2024-brief-mergers-acquisitions/#:~:text=Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,particularly%20in%20smaller%20healthcare%20markets'), AnnotationURLCitation(end_index=38301, start_index=38075, title='Antitrust & Competition Healthcare Quarterly Update Q2 2024 | Insights & Resources | Goodwin', type='url_citation', url='https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/09/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-quarterly-update-q2-2024#:~:text=,the%20Federal%20Trade%20Commission%E2%80%99s%20complaint'), AnnotationURLCitation(end_index=38496, start_index=38302, title='A Year-End Report for Healthcare Antitrust and What to Expect Later in 2025 | Insights | Holland & Knight', type='url_citation', url='https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=that%20healthcare%20transactions%20will%20remain,1')], text='# Federal Enforcement: Heightened Scrutiny of Healthcare Mergers\n\n**Aggressive Review of Deals:** U.S. antitrust agencies – the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) and Department of Justice (DOJ) – have sharply increased their scrutiny of mergers and acquisitions in the healthcare sector. In 2023, regulators challenged an unusually high number of healthcare deals, reflecting a belief that past merger review was too permissive ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=jointly%20announced%20the%20release%20of,Guidelines%20would%20remain%20in%20effect)) ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)). The FTC successfully **blocked several horizontal mergers** (e.g. hospital systems combining in the same region) using traditional antitrust theories that such deals would eliminate head-to-head competitors and harm patients through higher prices or lower quality ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=Commission%20,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)). Notably, in late 2023 a federal judge sided with the FTC to halt **IQVIA’s acquisition of Propel Media**, finding the merger of two leading healthcare marketing firms would stifle competition ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=FTC%20success%20in%20challenge%20to,a%20prolonged%20Second%20Request%20investigation)). Regulators are also pushing the boundaries with *novel theories of harm*: the new Merger Guidelines issued in late 2023 signal that enforcers will consider **impacts on labor (workers)** and **misuse of data** when evaluating healthcare mergers, and they explicitly caution that even minority shareholdings or serial acquisitions can raise antitrust concerns ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=agencies%20will%20continue%20to%20closely,from%20this%20path%20in%202024)) ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=jointly%20announced%20the%20release%20of,Guidelines%20would%20remain%20in%20effect)). This represents a more aggressive policy stance that **expands the types of transactions subject to challenge**, on the view that rampant consolidation in healthcare is driving up costs for consumers ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=jointly%20announced%20the%20release%20of,Guidelines%20would%20remain%20in%20effect)).\n\n**Challenging Big Pharma and Vertical Deals:** For the first time in over a decade, the FTC moved to block a major **pharmaceutical merger** on competitive grounds. In 2023 the FTC sued to stop Amgen’s $27.8 billion acquisition of Horizon Therapeutics – **even though the companies had no overlapping products** – arguing the deal would let Amgen use its portfolio power to undermine potential rivals to Horizon’s drugs and “maintain a monopoly” ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2023/05/16/ftc-amgen-horizon#:~:text=The%20Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,the%20FTC%20has%20permitted%20pharmaceutical)). (Historically the FTC allowed pharma mergers if overlapping drugs were divested, so this case marked a **tougher approach** ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2023/05/16/ftc-amgen-horizon#:~:text=purchasing%20Horizon%20Therapeutics%2C%20a%20rare,10%20billion%20between%202010%20and)).) The FTC ultimately settled that case by having Amgen agree not to bundle Horizon’s medications with its own, but the bold initial challenge signaled to the industry that **mergers lacking direct overlaps can still face antitrust attack**. Similarly, officials are casting a wary eye on vertical integration in health care – for example, the DOJ (joined by several states) **sued in late 2024 to block UnitedHealth Group’s proposed $3.3 billion takeover of Amedisys**, a home-health provider, over concerns a healthcare giant’s expanding empire could hurt competition in local markets ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/us-sues-block-unitedhealths-33-bln-purchase-amedisys-2024-11-12/#:~:text=2024,in%20the%20home%20health%20services)). (UnitedHealth’s Optum unit has been acquiring physician groups, clinics, and home care companies, raising alarms about a single company controlling many facets of care.) These enforcement moves – alongside the Biden Administration’s 2021 executive order calling out hospital consolidation and healthcare pricing issues – underscore that **antitrust officials are closely scrutinizing both horizontal and vertical deals** in healthcare and aren’t shying away from court fights.\n\n**New Guidelines and Filing Rules:** The antitrust agencies updated their Merger Guidelines and filing requirements to support this tougher enforcement climate. The **2023 Draft Merger Guidelines (finalized in late 2023)** explicitly highlight the healthcare sector, cautioning that the loss of competition can lead to higher medical costs and worse care outcomes. The Guidelines also emphasize that mergers increasing market concentration beyond certain thresholds are presumptively unlawful – reviving strict standards from earlier case law – and they endorse scrutiny of deals that **entrench power across multiple markets or along supply chains** ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=jointly%20announced%20the%20release%20of,Guidelines%20would%20remain%20in%20effect)). In practical terms, the FTC has enacted new **Hart–Scott–Rodino (HSR) filing rules** that demand far more information about deals at the time of notification ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=On%20Oct,The%20Final)). As of 2024, merging parties must disclose details like overlaps in product and service lines, distribution agreements, and the deal’s strategic rationale ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=On%20Oct,The%20Final)). This change (effective **late 2024**) significantly increases the burden of filing – the FTC estimates the average filing will take *around 100 hours of work*, up from ~37 hours previously ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=On%20Oct,The%20Final)). The goal is to catch subtler anticompetitive issues early, particularly in complex industries like healthcare where a merger’s impact on patients or innovation may not be obvious from basic revenue data.\n\n**DOJ Health Care Task Force:** In addition to rule changes, the DOJ Antitrust Division in 2024 formed a dedicated **“Task Force on Health Care Monopolies and Collusion”** to coordinate enforcement in this industry ([www.healthcareinsights.md](https://www.healthcareinsights.md/blog/2024/5/10/todays-news-and-commentary#:~:text=Assistant%20Attorney%20General%20Jonathan%20Kanter,businesses%20and%20entrepreneurs%2C%20including%20issues)) ([www.healthcareinsights.md](https://www.healthcareinsights.md/blog/2024/5/10/todays-news-and-commentary#:~:text=regarding%20payer,%E2%80%9D)). This inter-disciplinary task force – involving prosecutors, economists, physicians, and data scientists – is examining a wide range of concerns: **hospital-insurer consolidation, serial acquisitions of physician practices, healthcare labor markets, quality of care, billing practices, health IT, and even access to sensitive health data** ([www.healthcareinsights.md](https://www.healthcareinsights.md/blog/2024/5/10/todays-news-and-commentary#:~:text=The%20HCMC%20will%20consider%20widespread,%E2%80%9D)). By marshalling expertise across civil and criminal enforcement, the DOJ aims to identify anti-competitive conduct **beyond just mergers**, such as wage-fixing or collusive contracting in healthcare markets. (In fact, the DOJ saw its *first-ever criminal conviction* for labor-market antitrust in April 2025, when a home-health agency executive was convicted of conspiring to fix nurse wages ([www.antitrustalert.com](https://www.antitrustalert.com/category/healthcare-antitrust/#:~:text=DOJ%20Secures%20Its%20First,Criminal%20Antitrust%20Labor%20Market%20Trial)) – a sign that **antitrust law in healthcare is expanding into areas like employment practices**.) Overall, at the federal level the latest developments point to a more interventionist approach: regulators are requiring more upfront information, applying new theories, and dedicating special resources to **police consolidation in healthcare**.\n\n# Spotlight on Private Equity “Roll-Ups” in Healthcare\n\nA **major development in healthcare antitrust** is the targeting of private equity-led consolidation strategies. Private equity (PE) firms have been rapidly buying up medical practices, clinics, and specialist groups – often via a series of smaller acquisitions that individually fly under the radar. Studies indicate that **roughly 90% of PE-driven healthcare transactions are small enough to fall below federal HSR reporting thresholds** (which rose to $119.5 million in 2024) ([www.americanbar.org](https://www.americanbar.org/groups/business_law/resources/business-law-today/2024-may/may-2024-brief-mergers-acquisitions/#:~:text=Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,particularly%20in%20smaller%20healthcare%20markets)). This means many roll-ups (serial acquisitions) haven’t received federal antitrust review, even though collectively they can reduce competition in local markets ([www.americanbar.org](https://www.americanbar.org/groups/business_law/resources/business-law-today/2024-may/may-2024-brief-mergers-acquisitions/#:~:text=%24111,particularly%20in%20smaller%20healthcare%20markets)). In response, **antitrust enforcers have put PE in the crosshairs**. The FTC’s first lawsuit against a healthcare roll-up came in September 2023, when it sued PE firm Welsh, Carson, Anderson & Stowe over its strategy of consolidating anesthesiology practices in Texas ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=In%20September%202023%2C%20the%20FTC,may%20be%20the%20first%20of)). The FTC alleged that Welsh Carson orchestrated a scheme (through its portfolio company USAP) to buy up anesthesia provider groups and **corner the market** on hospital anesthesia services, driving up prices for patients and insurers ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=In%20September%202023%2C%20the%20FTC,may%20be%20the%20first%20of)). This bold “roll-up” case was widely seen as a *test* of whether antitrust law could reach a PE firm’s pattern of acquisitions.\n\n**Mixed Results in the Courts:** The enforcement push against PE roll-ups has encountered some legal hurdles. In May 2024, a federal judge *dismissed* the FTC’s claims against Welsh Carson, ruling that the agency’s lawsuit had not adequately tied the investor itself to antitrust violations by its portfolio company ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=focus%20was%20not%20always%20successful,minority%20investors%20in%20subsidiary%20companies)). The court’s dismissal clarified that **Section 13(b) of the FTC Act** (which allows the FTC to seek injunctions) cannot be used expansively to drag in outside minority investors unless there’s clear evidence of ongoing or imminent law violations ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=District%20Court%20for%20the%20Southern,minority%20investors%20in%20subsidiary%20companies)). In other words, the judge was wary of treating a PE owner as directly liable for a consolidation strategy executed via a subsidiary. This was a significant setback for the FTC’s novel approach to **punish PE firms for monopolistic roll-ups**. However, the story didn’t end there – in January 2025 the FTC reached a **settlement** with Welsh Carson to resolve potential administrative charges ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=that%20of%20stopping%20seemingly%20unfair,any%20future%20investments%20in%20anesthesia)). Under that settlement, the firm agreed to **curb its influence and notify regulators of future deals**: for example, Welsh Carson must limit its board seats and ownership stake in USAP, **obtain FTC approval before any new investments in anesthesia practices nationwide**, and give 30-days advance notice if it tries to acquire other hospital-based physician groups ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=announced%20a%20settlement%20with%20Welsh,based%20physician%20practices%20nationwide)). These unprecedented conditions function like ongoing antitrust guardrails, effectively placing a PE firm under monitoring for future healthcare acquisitions. The outcome signals that, despite a court rebuff, regulators are still finding ways to rein in serial acquisitions – and PE firms may face more scrutiny and **behavioral restrictions** when they seek to build healthcare empires.\n\n**Broader Impact and Political Pressure:** The intense focus on private equity’s role in healthcare extends beyond the FTC’s actions. Policymakers and researchers have raised alarms that PE ownership can lead to **cost-cutting at the expense of quality** – for instance, staffing reductions or surprise billing practices. In late 2024, the U.S. Senate Budget Committee released a report titled *“Profits Over Patients: The Harmful Effects of Private Equity on U.S. Health Care”*, concluding that PE investment often prioritizes short-term profits and can result in higher prices or diminished care quality in hospitals ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=Another%20example%20of%20the%20focus,provides%20in%20the%20healthcare%20industry)). This added political pressure bolsters the antitrust agencies’ resolve to scrutinize deals involving PE. We’re also seeing proposed legislation (at state and federal levels) specifically targeting PE acquisitions in health services. For example, some states have considered outright **bans on PE firms owning physician practices** or imposing special approval requirements (as discussed below). All of these developments indicate that **“roll-up” strategies are no longer flying under the radar** – they are front and center in antitrust discussions. Going forward, private equity buyers in healthcare should anticipate longer reviews, possible divestiture demands, and conditions to ensure competition isn’t harmed by a cumulative series of small deals.\n\n# Court Battles and Evolving Legal Standards\n\nThe recent wave of healthcare merger challenges has produced **mixed results in the courts**, leading to important legal developments. While antitrust enforcers have blocked some deals, judges have not sided with them in every case – refining the boundaries of antitrust law in this industry:\n\n- **Hospital Merger Injunctions – Wins and Losses:** Hospital consolidations remain a prime target for the FTC, but a notable 2024 ruling showed the FTC doesn’t win them all. In June 2024, a federal judge in North Carolina **denied the FTC’s request to preliminarily block Novant Health’s $320 million acquisition of two hospitals** from a rival system ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/ftc-loses-bid-block-320-million-hospital-merger-north-carolina-2024-06-05/#:~:text=A%20U,June%2026%2C%20with%20both%20sides)). The court found the FTC hadn’t met its burden to prove the deal would likely lessen competition substantially – even though Novant would control an estimated 65% of the local inpatient market. The judge noted potential **offsetting benefits** of the merger for those struggling community hospitals and questioned some of the FTC’s market definitions ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/ftc-loses-bid-block-320-million-hospital-merger-north-carolina-2024-06-05/#:~:text=Commission%27s%20,case%20is%20a%20part%20of)). This was a setback for the FTC’s hospital enforcement program, which had successfully stopped other mergers (e.g. in New Jersey and Utah in recent years) using more traditional analysis when hospitals were clear-cut competitors. The Novant case underscores that courts will still demand robust, fact-specific evidence of harm – especially if defendants argue that a merger may *improve* healthcare access or quality. It’s a reminder that **antitrust law requires weighing pro-competitive benefits against anti-competitive risks**, and healthcare defendants are using quality/improvement arguments to rebut the government’s claims.\n\n- **State Action (COPA Laws) vs. FTC:** Another legal development has been the tension between federal antitrust enforcement and **state laws that shield healthcare mergers**. Some states implement “**Certificate of Public Advantage (COPA)**” laws, which allow hospital systems to merge under state oversight (often to preserve struggling hospitals) and **immunize them from federal antitrust claims**. The FTC has long criticized COPA arrangements as enabling monopolies, but it suffered a defeat in 2023 trying to challenge them ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=in%20the%20FTC%E2%80%99s%20campaign%20against,antitrust%20laws%20supersede%20state%20COPA)). In a Louisiana case, a federal court **rejected the FTC’s argument that federal antitrust law should trump the state’s COPA statute**, firmly upholding the legality of the state-approved hospital merger ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=through%20Louisiana%E2%80%99s%20COPA%20statute%2C%20and,12)). The judge ruled that because the transaction was explicitly **authorized by state law and supervised by state authorities**, it was exempt from federal antitrust review under the “state-action” doctrine ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=campaigned%20against%20state,benefits%20of%20the%20deal%20outweigh)). This outcome affirms that, absent congressional change, COPA-sanctioned deals are largely beyond the FTC’s reach. Consequently, **some hospital systems in rural areas or smaller states have a path to consolidate by seeking a COPA from the state**, effectively trading competitive free-market oversight for state regulatory oversight. The FTC has expressed concern that this undermines antitrust enforcement, but courts indicate that **as long as states follow the requirements of active supervision, these mergers can proceed**. This development may encourage more hospitals to lobby for state COPA laws, although only a minority of states currently have them.\n\n- **Novel Theories Tested:** Courts are also grappling with how far new antitrust theories can go in healthcare M&A cases. The FTC’s **“bundled products” theory in pharma** (as seen in the Amgen/Horizon case) and the concept of mergers harming **labor markets (monopsony)** are relatively untested in litigation. While the Amgen case didn’t go to a final court decision (due to a settlement), it raised the question of whether a merger can be blocked for enabling anti-competitive *behavior* (like bundling different drugs in negotiations) even if it doesn’t eliminate a direct competitor. Similarly, the DOJ’s statements suggest that a hospital merger could be challenged for giving the combined system power to **push down nurses’ or doctors’ wages** (a monopsony harm) – a theory yet to be fully proven in court. Initial signs are that courts are cautious: they rely on established precedent that typically looks at **consumer prices and direct competition**, so enforcers will need strong evidence to succeed on these unconventional grounds. However, the inclusion of such theories in the new Merger Guidelines and public speeches means we may soon see test cases where the government argues a healthcare merger hurts not just patients as consumers, but also the **workers** who provide care or the **innovation pipeline** for new treatments. How courts rule on these arguments in upcoming cases will be a key development to watch, as it will determine the *scope* of antitrust law in the healthcare context moving forward.\n\n# State-Level Antitrust Measures on Healthcare Deals\n\nWith federal authorities stretched and many deals slipping under the radar, **state governments have started taking a more direct role in policing healthcare M&A**. The past two years have seen a flurry of state legislation and regulations aimed at increasing oversight of healthcare transactions:\n\n- **“Baby HSR” Laws – New Notification Requirements:** Numerous states are enacting their own **pre-merger notification mandates** for health sector deals. Unlike the federal HSR Act (which only requires notice for fairly large deals), these state laws kick in at much lower dollar thresholds or cover specific types of healthcare arrangements. **New York**, for example, implemented a **“Material Transactions” law in 2023** requiring that healthcare entities (hospitals, physician groups, insurance plans, clinical labs, pharmacies, etc.) give the state **90 days’ notice of any merger, acquisition, affiliation, joint venture, or similar transaction** meeting certain size criteria ([www.antitrustlawblog.com](https://www.antitrustlawblog.com/articles/healthcare-antitrust/#:~:text=The%20number%20of%20U,and%20Broader%29%20Areas%20of)) ([www.antitrustlawblog.com](https://www.antitrustlawblog.com/2025/04/articles/healthcare-antitrust/new-york-state-releases-much-anticipated-guidance-on-reporting-requirements-for-material-healthcare-transactions-as-budget-negotiations-near-conclusion-potentially-expanding-law-to-include-pre-closin/#:~:text=organization%2C%20or%20plan%20that%20provides,under%20the%20Material%20Transactions%20law)). The threshold is relatively low – **$25 million in combined annual revenue** for the parties – meaning even modest acquisitions or partnerships must be reported ([www.antitrustlawblog.com](https://www.antitrustlawblog.com/2025/04/articles/healthcare-antitrust/new-york-state-releases-much-anticipated-guidance-on-reporting-requirements-for-material-healthcare-transactions-as-budget-negotiations-near-conclusion-potentially-expanding-law-to-include-pre-closin/#:~:text=Clarification%20on%20the%20%2425%20Million,Threshold%20and%20%E2%80%9CDe%20Minimis%E2%80%9D%20Transactions)) ([www.antitrustlawblog.com](https://www.antitrustlawblog.com/2025/04/articles/healthcare-antitrust/new-york-state-releases-much-anticipated-guidance-on-reporting-requirements-for-material-healthcare-transactions-as-budget-negotiations-near-conclusion-potentially-expanding-law-to-include-pre-closin/#:~:text=The%20DOH%E2%80%99s%20examples%20clarify%20that,by%20%2425%20million%20or%20more)). The New York Department of Health can review these deals and even hold public hearings, adding transparency and allowing state officials to flag any competition concerns. **California** likewise passed a law (AB 2080) that took effect on January 1, 2024, requiring healthcare mergers and clinic acquisitions to be reported to the new Office of Health Care Affordability (OHCA) ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=California,have%20been%20reported%20to%20OHCA)). California’s regulations were updated mid-2024 to **cast an even wider net** – by mid-year, at least 11 transactions had already been reported to OHCA for review ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=California,have%20been%20reported%20to%20OHCA)). While California’s process is largely aimed at data collection and cost containment (the OHCA evaluates whether a deal might increase healthcare costs or undermine access), it creates a potential **pause** on deals until the state’s analysis is done. This trend of “Baby HSR” laws means that even if a deal is too small to alert the FTC, it may still face scrutiny and possible delay at the state level.\n\n- **Targeting Private Equity and Practice Acquisitions:** Many states are tailoring laws to address the very **private equity roll-ups** and rapid provider consolidation discussed above. **Massachusetts** is a prime example: since 2012 it has had a Healthcare Policy Commission (HPC) that monitors provider mergers for cost impacts, but in early 2025 the state expanded its law to shine a light on private equity investors ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=H,are%20in%20the%20following%20details)) ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=H.5159%20broadens%20the%20existing%2060,Massachusetts%20Health%20Policy%20Commission)). Under a new statute (H.5159, signed in Jan. 2025), Massachusetts broadened its mandatory health transaction reporting to include **any deal where a “significant private equity or investment entity” acquires a material stake in a healthcare provider or entity** ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=H.5159%20broadens%20the%20existing%2060,Massachusetts%20Health%20Policy%20Commission)) ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=,applicability%20of%20the%20amended%20law)). It also requires notice of **certain hospital real-estate transactions** (like sale-leaseback arrangements) and conversions of non-profit hospitals to for-profit status ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=1,the%20moment%2C%20many%20questions%20remain)). This law was crafted to increase transparency around **who is financing and controlling healthcare providers**, on the theory that ownership by PE or similar investors might warrant closer review. Other states are exploring even stricter measures: for instance, **Connecticut and Rhode Island** have debated limits on hospital ownership changes and **Minnesota** considered regulating physician practice management companies. Though not all proposals pass (California’s 2024 attempt to mandate *pre-approval* for any PE or hedge fund buying a healthcare entity was vetoed ([www.antitrustlawblog.com](https://www.antitrustlawblog.com/articles/healthcare-antitrust/#:~:text=On%20September%2028%2C%202024%2C%20Governor,of%20control%20of%20certain%20health))), the legislative trend is clearly toward **more oversight of acquisitions involving private investors** or those that could lead to provider monopolies in local markets.\n\n- **Broad Healthcare Merger Moratoria and Cost Oversight:** A few states have even gone as far as temporarily **banning certain mergers** or imposing cost controls on large systems. **Oregon** and **Washington** set up regulatory schemes requiring approval for mergers of hospitals or clinics above a low size threshold, focusing on whether the deal would reduce access or raise prices. Washington State made headlines in April 2025 by becoming the **first state to adopt the Uniform Antitrust Premerger Notification Act**, a law that actually applies to *all industries* but was driven in part by healthcare concerns ([www.antitrustalert.com](https://www.antitrustalert.com/category/healthcare-antitrust/#:~:text=Washington%20is%20the%20first%20state,includes%20significant%20penalties%20for%20noncompliance)). Washington’s law basically says if a merger requires a federal HSR filing and affects Washington, the same filing must be submitted to the state’s Attorney General ([www.antitrustalert.com](https://www.antitrustalert.com/category/healthcare-antitrust/#:~:text=Washington%20is%20the%20first%20state,includes%20significant%20penalties%20for%20noncompliance)). This ensures the state can independently review big healthcare deals (or any large deal) and even sue to block them alongside the federal agencies. On the other coast, **New York** not only has the notice law, but its Attorney General has been active in reviewing hospital mergers for antitrust issues, sometimes negotiating conditions or forcing abandonment of deals that the FTC might not have caught. States are also using **health commissions to monitor post-merger effects** – for example, Delaware’s Health Commission can require merging hospitals to report on pricing and quality for years afterwards. In sum, states are **filling gaps in enforcement** by catching smaller transactions and focusing on healthcare-specific metrics like patient costs, rural care availability, and whether investment-driven consolidations erode the quality of care.\n\nAll these developments at the state level mean that healthcare M&A now faces a **dual layer of antitrust oversight**: companies must navigate not only the FTC/DOJ process but also a patchwork of state reporting and approval rules. This can complicate deal timelines and strategies. However, it reflects policymakers’ concern that unchecked consolidation – whether it’s one giant hospital buying its competitor, or a private equity firm quietly amassing dozens of medical practices – can hurt consumers **even if** it escapes federal review. Going forward, we can expect continued experimentation by states, such as stricter merger **moratoria in healthcare “hot spots”** (e.g. limits on hospital mergers in highly consolidated regions) or new standards tying approval to commitments on price containment. Healthcare companies and investors must stay attuned to these state-law developments, as they are now a critical part of the **antitrust landscape for mergers and acquisitions**.\n\n# Key Takeaways and Outlook\n\n- **Antitrust Enforcement is Intensifying:** Recent years have seen a clear upswing in antitrust actions against healthcare mergers. Both the FTC and DOJ are more willing to challenge deals – even very large or novel ones – reflecting a view that consolidation has gone too far in the healthcare industry ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)) ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=jointly%20announced%20the%20release%20of,Guidelines%20would%20remain%20in%20effect)). From hospital systems and physician groups to health insurers and drug companies, no segment is off-limits. Merging parties should be prepared for closer scrutiny, longer investigations, and higher odds of litigation than in the past.\n\n- **New Theories and Broader Goals:** Antitrust enforcers are expanding their toolkit beyond classic price-and-market-share analysis. The **latest merger guidelines** emphasize potential harm to **workers (labor monopsony)** and to **innovation and data competition**, which are highly relevant in healthcare (e.g. the impact on nurse wages, or control of health data) ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=jointly%20announced%20the%20release%20of,Guidelines%20would%20remain%20in%20effect)). Regulators are also considering how a merger might facilitate future anti-competitive conduct (such as bundling products or exclusive contracting) even if it doesn’t create a monopoly overnight ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2023/05/16/ftc-amgen-horizon#:~:text=The%20Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,the%20FTC%20has%20permitted%20pharmaceutical)). This broader approach aligns with the Biden administration’s pro-competition agenda. Although there is some uncertainty about how aggressively these policies will continue under evolving leadership (the guidelines introduced in 2023 remain in effect into 2025 ([www.hklaw.com](https://www.hklaw.com/en/insights/publications/2025/01/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect#:~:text=approaches%20to%20merger%20review%20have,Guidelines%20would%20remain%20in%20effect))), **the overall trajectory is toward more vigilant antitrust enforcement in health care.**\n\n- **Courts as Crucial Arbiters:** The outcomes of recent cases show that **courts will ultimately refine the limits of antitrust law** in this arena. The FTC and DOJ have won significant victories blocking anti-competitive mergers, but they’ve also been **checked by judges when evidence of harm was deemed insufficient or when state policies conflicted with federal aims** ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/ftc-loses-bid-block-320-million-hospital-merger-north-carolina-2024-06-05/#:~:text=Commission%27s%20,case%20is%20a%20part%20of)) ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=through%20Louisiana%E2%80%99s%20COPA%20statute%2C%20and,12)). Going forward, watch for precedent-setting decisions – for example, if a court accepts or rejects a **labor harm theory** in a hospital merger, or how it handles a **Big Tech–meets–healthcare deal** (like a large data company buying a healthcare provider network). These decisions will shape how far agencies can go. So far, traditional horizontal mergers that create dominant local players are most likely to be blocked, whereas more novel theories must overcome skepticism. Companies should note that **even if they defeat a preliminary injunction (as Novant did) or evade federal jurisdiction (via a COPA law), enforcement pressure may continue through other means** – such as post-merger monitoring, state AG actions, or private lawsuits.\n\n- **State Enforcement is Here to Stay:** One of the latest and most significant developments is the rise of **state-level antitrust enforcement in healthcare**. States from New York to California to Massachusetts are not only **passing laws to review healthcare deals** ([www.antitrustlawblog.com](https://www.antitrustlawblog.com/articles/healthcare-antitrust/#:~:text=The%20number%20of%20U,and%20Broader%29%20Areas%20of)), but in some cases directly intervening to block or unwind mergers they find problematic. This decentralization means healthcare companies must engage with multiple regulators. A deal that sails through Washington could still snag in Sacramento or Albany. On the flip side, state initiatives could also complement federal efforts – for instance, by collecting data on smaller deals and market effects that the FTC can later use. We anticipate more states will adopt “mini-HSR” notification laws or strengthen their attorney generals’ authority to oversee health mergers in 2025 and beyond. The **patchwork of state rules** may be challenging for industry, but it’s a direct response to gaps perceived in federal enforcement (like the many sub-$119 million acquisitions that cumulatively reshape local markets ([www.americanbar.org](https://www.americanbar.org/groups/business_law/resources/business-law-today/2024-may/may-2024-brief-mergers-acquisitions/#:~:text=Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,particularly%20in%20smaller%20healthcare%20markets))).\n\n- **Continued Focus on Healthcare Costs and Competition:** Underlying these legal moves is a broad policy consensus that **healthcare consolidation has contributed to rising costs and needs to be checked**. Regulators cite studies linking hospital mergers to higher patient prices, or Nursing home chain buyouts to worse care outcomes. Thus, antitrust law is being wielded as one tool to address healthcare affordability and quality. We see this in the names of new state offices (e.g. “Health Care Affordability” in California) and in congressional rhetoric. Even if administrations change or specific cases falter, the **momentum for competitive healthcare markets** is likely to persist. Participants in the healthcare industry – hospitals, insurers, pharmaceutical companies, private equity funds, and others – should plan for a landscape where **mergers face more rigorous antitrust investigation than ever before**. In sum, the latest developments point to a tougher road for M&A in healthcare, as authorities at multiple levels push to prevent deals that could harm patients, payers, or the integrity of our healthcare system.
